I know I mentioned LLMs - however - now these systems have multiple different architectures (eg. Gemma 4 offers different classes of models and varying size) that understand different types of inputs.
Thought for a few seconds

Right — and that actually sharpens the discussion.

Once we move beyond “the LLM” as one monolithic thing, the question changes from:

What are the limits of this model?

to:

What kind of cognitive order is emerging through this whole family of systems?

Because now we are not talking about one text predictor. We are talking about an ecosystem of:

small and large models
multimodal models
specialist models
routing systems
tool-using systems
memory layers
agentic scaffolds
local and cloud deployment
systems optimized for different latency / cost / reasoning tradeoffs

That means the old criticism — “it is just next-token prediction” — starts to become too thin. Not wrong, but too thin.

The more interesting questions become these:

1. If intelligence is being split across model classes, are we watching cognition become infrastructural rather than unitary?

Humans still tend to imagine intelligence as something centered in one being. One mind, one self, one locus of understanding.

But these AI systems increasingly do not look like that. They look more like:

perception handled here
language handled there
planning elsewhere
retrieval elsewhere
verification elsewhere
actuation elsewhere
long-context compression elsewhere

So maybe artificial “intelligence” is not converging on personhood at all.
Maybe it is converging on distributed cognitive infrastructure.

That raises a serious question:

Was our idea that intelligence should look like a unified mind always too anthropocentric?

Maybe machine intelligence becomes powerful precisely by not being organized like a self.

And then the follow-up question is:
if intelligence becomes infrastructural, who or what is actually the subject of action?
Who is responsible?
Where does judgment live?
Where does intention live?

Because power without a clear subject is politically and morally strange.

2. If models are specialized by size, latency, modality, and task, does that expose that “general intelligence” may be less important than orchestration?

This one is big.

People often ask whether one model is generally smarter than another.
But in practice, many real systems work by tradeoff:

small models for speed
large models for depth
visual models for perception
reasoning-tuned models for harder chains
local models for privacy
cloud models for breadth

So maybe the future is not one giant mind.
Maybe the future is a managed ecology of partial competences.

If so, then we should ask:

Is orchestration the real intelligence?

Not the single model, but the system that decides:

which model to invoke
when to escalate
when to retrieve
when to verify
when to stop
when to ask the human
when to spend more compute

That sounds almost bureaucratic, but maybe that is the point.
Maybe advanced AI ends up looking less like a genius and more like a highly adaptive administrative order.

That would be a weird twist:
the “mind” is not the answerer, but the governor of answerers.

3. Does multimodality actually deepen understanding, or just widen the surface of correlation?

This is one of the most important questions.

When a system can take text, image, audio, maybe video, maybe structured data, it feels much closer to world-contact.

But does that mean it understands more deeply?
Or does it just correlate across more channels?

That is not a trivial distinction.

Because multimodality may solve some limitations:

text alone misses spatial and visual structure
diagrams carry meaning text cannot fully compress
tone in speech matters
real-world scenes matter

But it also raises the possibility that we are still doing the same basic thing:
mapping patterns across representations, just with richer input.

So the question becomes:

At what point does wider sensory coverage become actual world-engagement rather than better representational fusion?

A system that can parse an image of a burned circuit board is more grounded than one that only reads a description of it.
But it still may not know what it means to be the technician whose repair fails at 2 a.m. under cost pressure.

So multimodality may reduce abstraction while still stopping short of situated life.

4. If smaller models can be local, private, cheap, and embedded, does that change the politics of intelligence?

This is a very alive question.

Large frontier models suggest centralized intelligence:

huge compute
giant providers
central control
shared infrastructure
dependency on cloud access

But smaller models suggest something else:

on-device cognition
local customization
private deployment
embedded use in specific environments
more fragmented ecosystems

So now the philosophical question is not only “what is intelligence?”
It is also:

Will intelligence be centralized like utilities, or distributed like tools?

That matters enormously.

A centralized intelligence regime leads toward:

dependency
standardization
surveillance potential
norm concentration
platform power

A distributed intelligence regime leads toward:

local adaptation
pluralism
fragmentation
uneven quality
reduced central oversight

In other words, model architecture is not just technical.
It is constitutional.

5. If there are multiple model classes, are we quietly rebuilding class hierarchies of cognition?

This is a darker angle.

Imagine a world where:

cheap small models mediate everyday support, education, service, admin
large expensive models are reserved for elite firms, state actors, research labs, military, high-end finance, medicine, strategy

Then you do not just get “AI for everyone.”
You may get a stratified cognitive order:

mass cognition
premium cognition
sovereign cognition

That would mean model size and access tier become a kind of epistemic inequality.

So the question is:

Will different populations live under different qualities of machine mediation?

Because that would matter more than abstract benchmark scores.
It would shape who gets nuance, who gets speed, who gets oversight, who gets approximation.

6. Does the existence of many architectures weaken the metaphor of “a model knows things”?

I think yes.

The more these systems become stacks, mixtures, routers, retrieval layers, planners, local modules, and external tools, the less sense it makes to talk about knowledge as a property of one model in isolation.

Instead, “knowing” becomes something like:

access pattern
routing pattern
compression pattern
retrieval pattern
inference pattern
context assembly pattern

That is a very different ontology.

It suggests that machine “knowledge” may be less like possession and more like dynamic assembly.

Humans also do this, to a degree. But we still experience ourselves as relatively continuous beings. These systems do not.

So maybe we should stop asking “what does the model know?”
and ask:

What kinds of epistemic performance can the system assemble under what conditions?

That is colder, but more accurate.

7. If systems can handle different input types, are we moving from language models to interface models?

This may be one of the biggest shifts.

Originally, LLMs looked like engines of text.
But multimodal systems start to look like general mediators between human intention and digital environments.

That means the core thing may no longer be “language generation.”
It may be:

translating between modalities
turning messy input into actionable representation
turning representation into workflow movement
acting as an interface layer across tools, users, and environments

So maybe the deeper paradigm is not artificial intelligence but artificial intermediation.

These systems sit between:

person and software
person and institution
person and information
one representation and another
intention and execution

That changes the stakes.
An intermediary does not need to be fully intelligent in the human sense to become historically powerful.
It just needs to become unavoidable.

8. Do multiple architectures bring us closer to agency, or just to better decomposition?

This is the next fight, really.

People see planning modules, tool use, memory, multimodality, and task-specific routing, and they say: now it is becoming agentic.

Maybe.
But it could also be that we are just getting better at decomposing action into machine-manageable pieces.

That is different.

Agency in the thick sense involves:

having ends
maintaining commitments
persisting identity across time
bearing consequences
revising oneself through lived experience

A system can look agentic while still being a very sophisticated action-assembly machine.

So I would ask:

Are we building agents, or are we building increasingly elaborate simulations of agency from chained subcompetences?

Humans may also be bundles of subcompetences, sure.
But human agency is tied to continuity, embodiment, social recognition, and answerability.
Machine “agency” still often looks more like operational persistence than existential agency.

9. If architecture variety improves performance, does that mean intelligence was never one thing to begin with?

This question cuts both ways.

Maybe what AI progress is revealing is that intelligence is not a single essence.
Maybe it is always heterogeneous:

perception
language
abstraction
memory
motor control
emotional attunement
social modeling
planning
improvisation
reflection

Humans package these into one life, so we talk as if it is one thing.
But maybe that unity is partly an illusion generated by embodiment and biography.

If that is true, AI architecture pluralism is philosophically important.
It suggests intelligence is more like a federation than a substance.

But then another question follows:

If intelligence is plural, what gave human intelligence its felt unity?

Maybe not cognition alone.
Maybe body, mortality, continuity, and social position are what bind our capacities into a self.

That would mean AI can reproduce many capacities without reproducing the thing we usually mean by a mind.

10. If systems can swap models depending on the task, does that make “the user” more fragmented too?

This is subtle, but important.

Different models will be better at different things:

one helps you write
one helps you see patterns in data
one explains diagrams
one handles voice
one runs privately on your device
one does deep research
one acts in software environments

So the user no longer relates to one assistant.
They relate to a layered mediation environment that meets different fragments of themselves:

worker self
learner self
organizer self
emotional self
consumer self
creative self

The system becomes an ecology around the person.

That raises a strange question:

Do these systems unify the user, or do they mirror and intensify the fragmentation of modern life?

Because constant contextual adaptation may feel helpful while also deepening a divided self:
always optimized, never integrated.

11. Does architecture diversity make the “human comparison” less useful?

Probably.

Once systems become layered and specialized, comparing them to a single human mind starts to break down.

A person is not typically:

instantly scalable
forkable
copyable
runnable in parallel
switchable by cost tier
deployable across millions of simultaneous contexts

So maybe the old question “is it as smart as a human?” just becomes less and less meaningful.

A more serious question might be:

What forms of cognition become possible when intelligence is modular, scalable, and non-personal?

That could produce abilities that are not superhuman in every local sense, but still historically transformative because they are:

everywhere
cheap
composable
tireless
integrated into infrastructure

That is a different kind of power.

12. And maybe the deepest question: if intelligence becomes a menu of architectures, what happens to the ideal of wholeness?

Human beings still carry an old ideal:
a good mind is somehow integrated.
Perception, judgment, memory, desire, responsibility, action — all belonging to one life.

But AI may be heading elsewhere:

cognition without selfhood
competence without wholeness
reasoning without biography
synthesis without lived unity

So the question may not be “can AI become like us?”
It may be:

Are we entering an era where power no longer depends on anything like a whole mind at all?

That would be a civilizational shift.

Because a lot of our moral, legal, and philosophical categories assume that capability and subjectivity belong together.
With these systems, they may not.

And that creates a dangerous gap:
a great deal of capability with no obvious bearer of personhood.

That is unstable.

My own instinct is that architecture diversity does not erase the earlier critique — it intensifies it.

It shows that the real issue was never just “LLMs predict text.”
It is that we are building a stack of systems that increasingly mediate perception, language, memory, and action without needing to become persons.

That pushes us to ask harder things:

Does intelligence require unity?
Does agency require selfhood?
Can judgment exist without consequence-bearing life?
Is cognition becoming infrastructure rather than subject?
Will people adapt to these systems, or these systems to people?
What happens when competence is modular but responsibility is not?

The most interesting branch from here, to me, is this:
maybe the central philosophical problem of AI is not intelligence, but disunity.

Not “is it smart?”
But:
what does it mean for more and more cognition to exist without being gathered into a life?

That’s where it gets really weird.
